lls, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ingoldmells, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Ingoldmells, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldmells, Lincolnshire, England","Calthorp, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Muer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerd, Ingeburg.","German: habitational name for someone from Meura near Saalfeld (Thuringia) or Meuro near Wittenberg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":11,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":24,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":33,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Muer was born about 1304, in Ingoldmells, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Ralph de Muer Calthorpe, was 21 and her mother, Alice de Calthorpe, was 20. She married William Hiltoft about 1320, in England, United Kingdom. She died in 1350, in Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1304–1350":"umbes 1304–1350","1304–1350":"1304–1350","1313–1366":"1313–1366","1282–1366":"1282–1366","1327–1370":"1327–1370","1284–1332":"1284–1332","1285–1332":"1285–1332","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","about 1327":"umbes 1327","1366":"1366","1332":"1332","about 1303":"umbes 130